author: @TechLord79
text: You're funny, this might even be wxPython's lacking documentation fault: In (Windows) GUI programming everyone should now that a modal dialog is a blocking window; that is while the dialog window is open you are unable to interact with the program's main window. There are other "non-modal" dialogs or rather windows where you can work with a dialog/second window and the main window at the same time. That's why eg. .NET Form has "Show()" (non-modal) and "ShowDialog()" (modal) methods. Non-modal dialogs are used when immediate user interaction is required and the program cannot continue without it eg. selecting a file name.
